2.(c).
to create a file, write a student name, and close the file.
Pseudocode:
Step1:Use the header files <stdio.h>, <fcntl.h>, and <unistd.h>.
(<fcntl.h> is a header file in C used with system calls like open(), fcntl(), and creat())
Step 2: Declare an integer variable fd to store the file descriptor.
Step 3: Create a file using fd = creat("student.txt", 0644); (creat() is used to create a new file.)
Step 4: Write the student name into the file using write(fd, "John", 4); (write() is used to write data into the file.)
Step 5: Close the file using close(fd); (close() is used to close the file after completing the operation.)
Step 6: return 0 to end the program.

3.(a).
System calls required to copy the contents of one file to another
open() – Open the source file.
creat() or open() – Create/Open the destination file.
read() – Read data from the source file.
write() – Write data to the destination file.
close() – Close both files.
3.(b).
Purpose of any two system calls
1. read()-Reads data from the source file.
2. write()-Writes the data copied from source file into the destination file.
3.(c).
To copy the contents of one file to another:
Pseudo-code
Step 1: Use header files <stdio.h>, <unistd.h>, and <fcntl.h>.
Step 2: Open the source file using open().
Step 3: Create/Open the destination file using creat() (or open()).
Step 4: Read data from the source file using read().
Step 5: Write the data to the destination file using write().
Step 6: Repeat Steps 4 and 5 until the end of the source file is reached.
Step 7: Close both files using close().

4.(a).
The purpose of the fork() and exec() system call:
fork()-This system call helps in the creation of the new child process.
exec() – This system call is used to execute a new program by replacing the current process with the specified program.
4.(b).
The role of wait() system call:
The wait() system call ensures that the parent process waits untill the child process completes its execution and continues only after the children process is completed.  
